00:04:22,520 --> 00:04:33,680
 by making three consecutive comments, all on the issue of methodology.

25
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:40,440
 After expounding how the New Testament builds on the foundations of the Old in order to

26
00:04:40,440 --> 00:04:50,840
 tell us who we are, why we are here, and how we are to live, Chris, at the start of his

27
00:04:50,840 --> 00:05:03,680
 fourth lecture this evening, brought up the final question, where will it all end? He

28
00:05:03,680 --> 00:05:13,960
 suggests that the Bible is a meta-narrative. It tells a big story that runs from Genesis

29
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:23,960
 to Revelation, from creation to new creation. He also makes use of the analogy of the Bible

30
00:05:23,960 --> 00:05:33,440
 as a great drama, portraying the great sweep of the drama in seven acts—creation, rebellion,

31
00:05:33,440 --> 00:05:43,180
 promise, Christ, mission, judgment, new creation—all on a napkin, remember. It is on this analogy

32
00:05:43,180 --> 00:05:52,560
 of the Bible as meta-narrative, or a drama in seven acts, that I would like to raise

33
00:05:52,560 --> 00:06:01,840
 my first comment. In his monograph, Dominion and Dynasty—A

34
00:06:01,840 --> 00:06:09,880
 Analogy of the Hebrew Bible, published in 2003 by Apollos and InterVarsity Press, a

35
00:06:09,880 --> 00:06:22,840
 Canadian scholar, Stephen Dempster, argues that despite its undoubted literary diversity,

36
00:06:22,840 --> 00:06:34,840
 the Hebrew Bible possesses a remarkable structural and conceptual unity. Readers may hence find

37
00:06:34,840 --> 00:06:44,400
 a comprehensive narrative framework which provides an overarching literary and historical

38
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:53,040
 context. Dawn Carson, another world-renowned New Testament scholar who is also the series

39
00:06:53,040 --> 00:07:00,080
 editor, is of the opinion that Dempster's reading of the storyline of the Old Testament

40
00:07:00,080 --> 00:07:13,480
 is fresh, provocative, helpful. The book comprises nine chapters, and between his introduction,

41
00:07:13,480 --> 00:07:20,320
 chapter one, and conclusion, chapter nine, Dempster reviews the storyline in the middle

42
00:07:20,320 --> 00:07:30,440
 six chapters, following the order of the Hebrew canon. The narrative storyline begins from

43
00:07:30,440 --> 00:07:38,520
 Genesis and continues in the other four books, that is Exodus to Deuteronomy, after Torah,

44
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:46,240
 and the next four books, Joshua to Kings, of the former prophets. He gives this first

45
00:07:46,240 --> 00:07:57,040
 part of the biblical narrative the theme, "Dominion lost, the rise and fall of Israel."

46
00:07:57,040 --> 00:08:08,800
 The second part, Dempster labels as "retrospect" and "prospect," a "stump" and a "shoot,"

47
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:17,120
 and he calls this middle part, interestingly, a "suspension" of the storyline. When the

48
00:08:17,120 --> 00:08:24,360
 poetic commentary begins with the four books, Jeremiah, Ezekiel, Isaiah, and the twelfth

49
00:08:24,360 --> 00:08:33,120
 of the latter prophets, and continues into another seven books of the writings. This

50
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:40,360
 is the second part. Finally, the third part marks the ending of poetic commentary and

51
00:08:40,360 --> 00:08:48,400
 resumption of narrative storyline. In the last four books, Esther, Daniel, Ezra, Nehemiah,

52
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:56,640
 and Chronicles of the writings, and Dempster calls this part, "Dominion regained, the fall

53
00:08:56,640 --> 00:09:09,720
 and rise of Israel." By insisting on not losing sight of the forest, that is, taking seriously

54
00:09:09,720 --> 00:09:20,160
 the canonical structure of the Tanakh, Dempster honestly admits that his narrative storyline

55
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:31,200
 covers no more than 13 of the 24 books, or just one book more than half of the Hebrew

56
00:09:31,200 --> 00:09:41,400
 scripture. The other 11 books he concedes to be poetic commentary, which also implies

57
00:09:41,400 --> 00:09:50,680
 a suspension of the storyline. Thanks to his scholarly integrity, readers may become aware

58
00:09:50,680 --> 00:10:01,120
 of the fact that the so-called "meta-narrative" of the Old Testament constitutes perhaps only

59
00:10:01,120 --> 00:10:12,880
 the first half of the picture, leaving the second half a commentary and suspension.

60
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:22,080
 My first comment is, therefore, why not the other way round, taking Chayotz Geshishtah

61
00:10:22,080 --> 00:10:31,320
 as a literary context for faith and work in the historical realities of the 5th Berith

62
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:42,000
 Olam (Everlasting Covenant), or even better, a consistently coherent periquoesis of Torah,

63
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:54,000
 Abiyim, and Ketuvim, altogether leaving behind both the logical system of dogmatics, where

64
00:10:54,000 --> 00:11:02,320
 eschatology always comes last, and the linear progression of historical revelation, when

65
00:11:02,320 --> 00:11:12,000
 there must still be a better future lying in wait for us.

66
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:20,880
 My second comment begins with the succinct summary statement Chris makes regarding hope

67
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:30,560
 in the New Testament. "Christian hope is not blind optimism, but rather the assured

68
00:11:30,560 --> 00:11:39,120
 biblical certainty that the future is in God's hands, and God's sovereign purpose will

69
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:47,960
 ultimately be accomplished in the reconciliation and restoration of his whole creation, along

70
00:11:47,960 --> 00:11:56,960
 with the redemption of people from every tribe and nation and language; and indeed, that

71
00:11:56,960 --> 00:12:09,400
 hope has already been accomplished in anticipation through the cross and resurrection of Jesus

72
00:12:09,400 --> 00:12:19,360
 Christ." I think this is a very important, succinct summary of what hope is in the New

73
00:12:19,360 --> 00:12:29,920
 Testament. The center is in the cross and the resurrection of Jesus Christ. Christian

74
00:12:29,920 --> 00:12:40,600
 hope, in other words, is grounded on the biblical confession of the monotheistic faith. And

75
00:12:40,600 --> 00:12:48,640
 I quote another Old Testament scholar, James Sanders, "What do we mean by monotheistic

76
00:12:48,640 --> 00:12:58,280
 faith?" He has a very unique perspective on this particular theme. To monotheize, Sanders

77
00:12:58,280 --> 00:13:11,240
 said, is not to progress or evolve toward monotheism, but rather to struggle within

78
00:13:11,240 --> 00:13:24,680
 and against polytheistic contexts to affirm God's oneness, both in antiquity and today.

79
00:13:24,680 --> 00:13:33,560
 This is what he calls canonical hermeneutics in his book Canon and Community, A Guide to

80
00:13:33,560 --> 00:13:44,720
 Canonical Criticism, published in 1984. He goes on to emphasize that the interest was

81
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:54,600
 in what God was doing in and through the givens of the situation described, and what God might

82
00:13:54,600 --> 00:14:03,520
 do again. God is presented as creator, sustainer, judge, redeemer, and re-creator insofar as

83
00:14:03,520 --> 00:14:15,860
 we can discern the interest was never anthropocentric or primarily sociological or political, not

84
00:14:15,860 --> 00:14:26,200
 in the way the various accounts, biblical narrative are presented canonically. The interest

85
00:14:26,200 --> 00:14:34,880
 was in what God as creator and redeemer could do with the social conditions or the political

86
00:14:34,880 --> 00:14:44,440
 situation. To moralize in reading a text is to focus on and even absolutize the cultural

87
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:53,440
 mores and conditions thereof. To theologize in reading a text is to focus on what God

88
00:14:53,440 --> 00:15:02,680
 can do with the likes of the reader mirrored in the text.

89
00:15:02,680 --> 00:15:10,760
 To recapitulate just a couple of examples of this canonical hermeneutics from Scripture

90
00:15:10,760 --> 00:15:22,040
 again, when Malachi concluded with the coming of the day of the Lord, he referred his audience

91
00:15:22,040 --> 00:15:34,920
 back to the classical days of Moses and Elijah. And so did Jesus during his transfiguration.

92
00:15:34,920 --> 00:15:41,900
 The final vision Ezekiel saw during the darkest hours of the Babylonian exile regarding the

93
00:15:41,900 --> 00:15:48,960
 rebuilding of New Jerusalem brought up the wilderness experience of the twelve tribes

94
00:15:48,960 --> 00:15:59,200
 in the beginning chapters of the book of Numbers, a reference reappearing again in the final

95
00:15:59,200 --> 00:16:07,440
 vision of the church in Revelation 21. And the mentioning of a new heaven and a new earth

96
00:16:07,440 --> 00:16:16,400
 in Isaiah 65, also the passage quoted at its end, the same imagery from Isaiah chapter

97
00:16:16,400 --> 00:16:27,160
 11, where the promise of Emmanuel was firmly anchored in the aftermath of the brief Syro-Aphramatic

98
00:16:27,160 --> 00:16:36,080
 invasion. It is apparently against our religious instinct

99
00:16:36,080 --> 00:16:47,480
 to look for hope not in the future days to come, but back to the historical past to witness

100
00:16:47,480 --> 00:16:55,160
 the sovereignty of our one true God. Yet this is exactly what the Holy Scripture is trying

101
00:16:55,160 --> 00:17:05,920
 to emphasize time and again, to bring us back to this monotheistic faith declared right

102
00:17:05,920 --> 00:17:14,920
 from the very beginning of the creation of heaven and earth.

103
00:17:14,920 --> 00:17:25,060
 This brings us to my last comment. And I would like to quote John Webster from one of his

104
00:17:25,060 --> 00:17:32,880
 essays, The Dogmatic Location of the Canon, in his collection, The Word and Church, Essays

105
00:17:32,880 --> 00:17:40,960
 in Christian Dogmatics, published in 2001. And this is what he says. "If the canon, that

106
00:17:40,960 --> 00:17:47,800
 is the Bible, Holy Scripture, is a function of God's communicative fellowship with the

107
00:17:47,800 --> 00:17:56,960
 unruly church," notice adjective, unruly, rebellious, "if it is part of the history

108
00:17:56,960 --> 00:18:06,520
 of judgment and mercy," that is, the Bible is part of this history of judgment and mercy,

109
00:18:06,520 --> 00:18:18,120
 "then the Bible, the canon, Scripture, cannot simply be a stabilizing factor or a legitimating

110
00:18:18,120 --> 00:18:30,640
 authority. Rather, as the place where divine speech may be heard, it is, or ought to be,

111
00:18:30,640 --> 00:18:41,280
 a knife at the church's heart." I like this imagery.

112
00:18:41,280 --> 00:18:51,720
 During the first two decades in the history of our school, CGST, our first year students

113
00:18:51,720 --> 00:18:59,440
 enrolled in two respective courses in Old Testament and New Testament theology, and

114
00:18:59,440 --> 00:19:09,440
 then moved on to four courses in doctrinal theology in their subsequent years. First,

115
00:19:09,440 --> 00:19:18,840
 biblical theology, then doctrinal theology. At the curriculum review of the mid-90s, we

116
00:19:18,840 --> 00:19:27,520
 switched the order and asked our students to study the first two courses in dogmatics

117
00:19:27,520 --> 00:19:34,520
 during their first year, then two more courses in dogmatics together with two biblical theology

118
00:19:34,520 --> 00:19:45,400
 courses in their second year. The rationale behind was that biblical theology is no longer

119
00:19:45,400 --> 00:19:57,120
 to serve as the proof-text for Christian theology, but rather, biblical theology becomes a necessary

120
00:19:57,120 --> 00:20:07,520
 critique on our dogmatic thinking. Such is the practice in theological education of the

121
00:20:07,520 --> 00:20:16,560
 Reformation principle of sola scriptura. The authority of Scripture does not begin with

122
00:20:16,560 --> 00:20:24,680
 a single word God breathed and then proceed on to metaphysical polemics about infallibility

123
00:20:24,680 --> 00:20:33,600
 or inerrancy, but rather should explore how the Word of God, not just God breathed, but

124
00:20:33,600 --> 00:20:44,240
 also is useful for teaching, for rebuking, for correcting, and for training in righteousness,

125
00:20:44,240 --> 00:21:02,280
 so that the men of God, men and women of God, may be thoroughly equipped for every good

126
00:21:02,280 --> 00:21:15,560
 work (2 Timothy 3:16-17). So, returning to the theme of hope, what has the Holy Scripture

127
00:21:15,560 --> 00:21:28,560
 to rebuke and correct our ecclesiastical traditions and apologetic orthodoxy? Chris aptly concludes

128
00:21:28,560 --> 00:21:34,880
 his final lectures in saying that it is the Old Testament that shaped the New Testament's

129
00:21:34,880 --> 00:21:45,880
 vision of the future, centered on Christ and His victory, and extended to every sinner,

130
00:21:45,880 --> 00:21:54,160
 to all nations, and to the whole creation. Let us briefly re-examine once more these

131
00:21:54,160 --> 00:22:05,800
 three foci of hope for sinners, hope for the nations, and hope for creation.

132
00:22:05,800 --> 00:22:06,800
 Hope for Sinners

133
00:22:06,800 --> 00:22:20,000
 God rewards the good and punishes the bad. This is accepted by every folk religion. It

134
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:32,360
 is only our Bible that talks about a God who pardons sinners and calls His own people to

135
00:22:32,360 --> 00:22:43,800
 follow the footsteps of His beloved Son to suffer on their behalf. Remember Joshua, the

136
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:56,280
 Jesus of the Greek Septuagint. He saved not only Rahab the prostitute and her family from

137
00:22:56,280 --> 00:23:06,440
 the ruins of Jericho, but also the Hivites living in Gibeon. One of the seven Canaanite

138
00:23:06,440 --> 00:23:22,320
 tribes deserved to be destroyed from being killed by the Israelites. Do Christians rejoice

139
00:23:22,320 --> 00:23:37,280
 when we see our enemies, the bad guys, being judged and condemned or forgiven?

140
00:23:37,280 --> 00:23:38,280
 Hope for Sinners

141
00:23:38,280 --> 00:23:57,720
 To the audience of Prophet Isaiah, that Egypt and Assyria, both archenemies of Israel, would

142
00:23:57,720 --> 00:24:07,860
 be blessed by the Lord was definitely a distant hope, if not wishful thinking. But today,

143
00:24:07,860 --> 00:24:17,480
 we have Christian seminaries in both Cairo and Baghdad, just like here in Hong Kong.

144
00:24:17,480 --> 00:24:25,900
 The Christian gospel has indeed transformed the history and culture of each and every

145
00:24:25,900 --> 00:24:39,000
 continent, and it is happening right before our eyes here in Asia today. Hope for the

146
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:49,780
 nations may no longer be a far-off dream 2,000 years after Pentecost. But what about the

147
00:24:49,780 --> 00:24:59,520
 same old prophetic promise which bonded Egypt and Assyria together with Israel? Are we able

148
00:24:59,520 --> 00:25:08,720
 to maintain fellowship among a Messianic Jew, a Palestinian Christian, and a Muslim background

149
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:21,680
 brother? Do we see our Israeli colleagues and Jewish friends, not Christians, as a people

150
00:25:21,680 --> 00:25:33,320
 of the everlasting covenant, hence the root feeding the church? And that, looked at from

151
00:25:33,320 --> 00:25:42,940
 the long-range perspective of God's overall purpose, they, the Jewish people, they remain

152
00:25:42,940 --> 00:26:00,720
 God's oldest friends. God's gifts and God's call are under full warranty, never cancelled,

153
00:26:00,720 --> 00:26:04,080
 never rescinded.

154
00:26:04,080 --> 00:26:14,000
 Last, but definitely not least, hope for creation. My time is up, so I shall only focus on Isaiah

155
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:21,720
 65, as this half-chapter is not just the first among the four biblical passages mentioning

156
00:26:21,720 --> 00:26:28,680
 the new heavens and the new earth, but also the fullest and perhaps the definitive statement

157
00:26:28,680 --> 00:26:38,720
 for our understanding. The concluding verse on the wolf and the lamb, the lion and the

158
00:26:38,720 --> 00:26:50,920
 ox, immediately rings a bell, because back in Isaiah 11, verses 6 to 9, the same imagery,

159
00:26:50,920 --> 00:27:00,960
 a metaphor, is applied as an extended metaphor to the Davidic king and his duty to uphold

160
00:27:00,960 --> 00:27:11,320
 justice among his people. The New Testament tells us our Lord reminds the faithful and

161
00:27:11,320 --> 00:27:23,640
 wise servants to carry out their appointed tasks while waiting for the Master's return.

162
00:27:23,640 --> 00:27:35,160
 Christian hope is not blind optimism, nor is it passive waiting, keeping our fingers

163
00:27:35,160 --> 00:27:43,800
 crossed that everything will get better and better and turn out okay in the end. No, our

164
00:27:43,800 --> 00:27:55,680
 hope is integrated indeed with our mission, as well as our ethics, as it is grounded in

165
00:27:55,680 --> 00:28:09,480
 our identity. Yes, faith in Christ Jesus, love for all the saints, and hope in heaven

166
00:28:09,480 --> 00:28:23,640
 holds Trill, or Trinity, in Colossians chapter 1. But all three, never, no, not in a far

167
00:28:23,640 --> 00:28:33,280
 distant future, but right here and now. Remember, in 1 Corinthians, it is not hope that comes

168
00:28:33,280 --> 00:28:46,760
 at the end, it's love. So thank you, Chris, for a series of very biblical and thought

169
00:28:46,760 --> 00:28:55,560
 provoking lectures. I'm trying my very best to find bones in an egg, but I'm doomed to

170
00:28:55,560 --> 00:29:17,720
 failure, of course. So, I'll hand the time back to the Chairman.

